metadata.name: Annihilate This Week #319
metadata.description:
This is a companion piece to "Saturday Night's Alright (For Fighting)" (project #14045). Same algorithm of the previous one, only slightly modified, the main difference is that here the daily variations are all mixed up together and the output doesn't change based on the current day.

This is intended to be a gift for all collectors and the community of fx(hash) that showed so much support for the "Saturday" project, really beyond my expectations.

50% of the royalties goes to the minter, do with the piece whatever you'd like, hold it, sell or trade it, or even burn it if you really don't like it :)

Thank you!

----

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Dencity #714
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ‚ù§Ô∏è, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Gonzion #12
metadata.description:
Gonzion is a Non-Linear Iterated Function System rendered using a method similar to Fractal Flames of Electric Sheep fame.

Technological tendrils from beyond light-aeons draw ancient crystals, transmuted fungus, sentient sigils in fossilized dimensions and alien topologies.

It's not built to run on a (2022) mobile phone and has been known to crash some, but runs fine on others.

For higher resolution renders add "#N" to the URL, default N=2.

metadata.name: Mountain Moves #40
metadata.description:
Mountain Moves - ...kind of the logical real-time consequence of "Mountain View"
featuring different mountain formation (noise) types, different display modes
(outlines, semi outlines, no outlines, soft paint strokes)
6 color modes are still switchable. initially always 2-color modes.
on phones also uses device orientation.
 
 press 'c' ... switch color mode
 press 's' ... save png of actual resolution x3

metadata.name: Heavy Light #174
metadata.description:
This is an experiment in spaces lit by falling particles of light.

Each particle draws a thin trace as it falls and changes its colour whenever it reflects from a wall or an obstacle. 

The piece takes some time to fully render. After the signature appears on the bottom of the picture, you are free to hit 's' to save a high resolution PNG for printing and seeing the finer details.

The work features 5 different canvas sizes and 8 palettes.

metadata.name: Crosswords #3
metadata.description:
Crosswords is an abstract representation of the challenges that life puts in front of us daily. We just need to find the right answer that fits the empty tiles to accomplish everything. Impossible is nothing.

Color palettes are inspired by the great artworks of Donald Judd.

By refreshing the screen on different window sizes the artwork will adapt and the position and dimension of the tiles might change.
In this way, I want to mimic the infinite crosswords we need to solve in our lifetime.

hit 's' on live view to save a png of the current view.

Press 's' to save PNG (live mode only).

metadata.name: Unfolded #153
metadata.description:
A plane is repeatedly folded over itself, choosing creases either at random, or according to some pattern (like a grid). These creases form the boundaries of the individual textured tiles.

Once the folds are complete, they are undone in reverse order, recreating the original plane. With each unfolding, the orientation of each crease (as a mountain or a valley), and each tile (facing up or down) is recorded as a sequence of 1s and 0s. Tiles are colored and textured according to similarities in these binary sequences, giving rise to subtle symmetries and repetitions.

Written in vanilla JS & HTML5 Canvas.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: dg5721() #66
metadata.description:
A tiny neural network with 5721 neurons, that tries to imitate human handwriting by generating new hallucinated digits in real-time.

It can generate these digits at any resolution and will invent its own ways to fill the gaps.

- Press <SPACE> or click to toggle the infinite latent space exploration.
- Press <S> to save the current frame as PNG at the current screen resolution x2.

It can be installed to work offline (Install button in the URL bar in Chrome or "Add to Home screen" on iOS)

As of 2021, this artwork requires a fast computer or mobile phone.
